library("ggplot2")

Uniform Distribution

  1. Demonstrate your understanding about the example code block below by adding at least 5 comments in the code block in your own words.
N <- 1000   #assigns variable N value 1000
a <- 1      #assigns variable a value 1
b <- 32     #assigns variable b value 32
data <- runif(N, a, b) #creates iteratible of 1000 elements randomly between 1 and 32
df <- data.frame(data) #makes dataframe with iteratible data as column and calls it df

ggplot(df, aes(y = data)) +   #Creates boxplot with data from df. 
  coord_flip() +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = paste0("Uniform Distribution U(", a, ",", b, ")"), #label it "Uniform Distribution"
       subtitle = "boxplot",
       caption = "Math 32") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  ylim(0,50) #Limit y axis to between 0 and 50

ggplot(df, aes(x = data)) +   #Creates graph of density by number
  geom_density(kernel = "gaussian") +
  labs(title = paste0("Uniform Distribution U(", a, ",", b, ")"),
       subtitle = "density plot",
       caption = "Math 32") +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  xlim(0,50)  #Limit x axis to between 0 and 50

Normal Distribution

  1. Make adjustments to the code below to repeat what was done above with the uniform distribution, but this time looking at the normal distribution (hint: use the rnorm command).
N <- 1000
a <- 1
b <- 32
data <- rnorm(N, a, b)
df <- data.frame(data)

ggplot(df, aes(y = data)) +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = paste0("Normal Distribution N(", a, ",", b, ")"),
       subtitle = "boxplot",
       caption = "Math 32") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),

  1. Make adjustments to the code below to repeat what was done above with the uniform distribution, but this time looking at the exponential distribution with \(\lambda = \frac{1}{\mu}\) (hint: use the rexp command).
N <- 1000
mu <- 32
data <- rexp(N,mu)
df <- data.frame(data)

ggplot(df, aes(y = data)) +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = paste0("Exponential Distribution E(1/", mu, ")"),
       subtitle = "boxplot",
       caption = "Math 32") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  ylim(-.1,.3)
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

ggplot(df, aes(x = data)) +
  geom_density() +
  labs(title = paste0("Exponential Distribution E(1/", mu, ")"),
       subtitle = "density plot",
       caption = "Math 32") +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
